I'm curious as to the reason that one would want undefined and null values ignored?

*(This is happening on [line 9 of Object.js](https://github.com/paularmstrong/normalizr/blob/master/src/schemas/Object.js#L9))*

**Input**

I have a schema similar to the following:
```js
cosnt simpleItemSchema = new schema.Entity('simpleItems');

const complexItemSchema = new schema.Entity('complexItems', {
  nested: {
    simpleItem: simpleItemSchema
  },
  ...
});
```
Now, `nested.simpleItem` will sometimes be `null`; and it being `null` has some special significance because it means that it was specifically set to `null`.

**Output**

The property `nested.simpleItem` is omitted from the normalization of any "complexItem". This creates a problem due to the fact that `null` has meaning here and if the property is not present, one cannot assume that the value might be null or undefined. _(I'm doing some diffing and whatnot, hence the need for the presence of the property)_.

**Question/Request**

Would it be reasonable to want to add an option to not omit `null` values or to not omit the `null` value so long as a property's schema is an `EntitySchema`?

